article.headline: Sting hit 12 3-pointers to hand Sparks first loss
article.linkText: Miller helps Sting hand champion Sparks first loss
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Kelly Miller scored a career-high 23
points, including a 3-pointer in overtime, as the Charlotte Sting
beat defending WNBA champion Los Angeles 94-87 on Saturday night.

	   Miller, filling in for injured scoring star Andrea Stinson, hit
a 3-pointer from the corner with 2:20 left to give the Sting an
88-82 lead. Miller, who had a disappointing rookie season a year
ago, bested her previous career high by 16 points.

	   "I knew I needed to step up,'' Miller said. "I went out and
played hard. I got great passes from my teammates.''

	   Charlotte (1-0) hit a team-record 12 3-pointers in 21 attempts,
including 4-of-4 shooting from Miller. Dawn Staley added 19 points
and nine assists.

	   Lisa Leslie had 26 points and 12 rebounds to lead the Sparks
(3-1), but she fouled out with 1:07 remaining in overtime. Latasha
Byears added 15 points, but also fouled out in OT.

	   "We had this unbeaten thing going, but it's over now,'' Sparks
coach Michael Cooper said. "Charlotte had a great game plan, but
our goal now is what it ought to be, and that's to win a
championship.''

	   With the game tied, Leslie missed a half-hook in the lane with
20 seconds left in regulation, and Staley's runner in the lane was
blocked by Nikki Teasley to force overtime.

	   Stinson twisted her left ankle defending DeLisha Milton in the
high post with 7:58 left in the first half and did not return.

	   The Sting were swept by the Sparks in two games in last year's
finals.

	   "We made a strong statement tonight,'' Sting coach Anne Donovan
said. "Fourteen other teams just woke up and realized we are for
real.''

	   Former Boston Celtics player, coach and executive M.L. Carr
attended the game, two days after he was hired as president of the
Sting. Carr is also a part of a Larry Bird-led ownership group
interested in bringing an NBA expansion team to Charlotte to
replace the Hornets, who have moved to New Orleans.
